She flipped to a blank page and wrote the date on it. Then, she wrote below the date: "5/11/648-12/13/648".
"Looking back on the past?" Avery asked, looking at the old notebook. Carly nodded. "Do you think they'll let you go out for Christmas? There are only a few days left until Christmas."
Carly tapped the lantern twice to indicate "no," as Avery had expected. The Ice King would never allow Carly to go outside, as she was, in his eyes, "a flaw." Carly was born mute and was the only girl in the family; all the other children were boys.
Avery was also treated in the same way, in TA's unique manner. When Avery publicly appeared as a non-binary individual, the world seemed to change as well. As a punishment for TA's uniqueness, TA was mostly assigned to work alone for most of the time.
TA was also forced to be the princess's servant. However, TA didn't mind, because TA had a friend.
"Your birthday is coming up, right?" Avery asked, remembering that in a few more days it would be the princess's birthday. Carly nodded, a flicker of sadness passing through her pale blue eyes.
"Would you like to celebrate?" TA asked, recalling how Carly had answered this question last time.
No. Carly tapped the table. Avery knew this was a difficult subject for Carly to bring up. On that day, she was imprisoned in this room while her mother was executed. Avery was still an infant when it happened, but TA remembered the anger of the servants and the citizens. TA heard that Queen Elvin was a good queen and could magically predict future events.
"So... what would you like to do?" TA asked. Carly looked up at TA, filled with excitement. She handed Avery a piece of paper. However, when he looked down at it...
6 inches X 6 inches canvas
White, varying shades of blue paint
6 brushes of different sizes
Easel
"Are you trying to get me to find these things for you?" Avery turned to the silent princess, who was constantly tapping and her ponytail swaying back and forth. "Is that right?" When TA saw the usually quiet and reserved princess so enthusiastic about something, TA couldn't help but giggle. This was the first time she wanted something outside her room, and it had nothing to do with books.
"Okay! Then, see you later?" Avery said, standing up and moving through the messy papers and notebooks.
Carly nodded and continued to curl deeper into the thick blankets, recalling her memories.
TA left the room, feeling relieved that the princess was finally willing to try something new and had made some requests beyond her abilities (such as paint).
TA crossed the hall again, trying not to pay attention to the servants' hushed whispers.
"I heard she's been possessed by Queen Elvin, so she always goes to that room."
"I heard she eats children in that room."
"Does she look like a man? Is that normal?"
TA couldn't take it anymore and had to cover their ears. TA headed to the royal painter's room, which was the second door on the left in the east wing.
Avery arrived at the door, which was as elaborately decorated as Carly's. The door featured a white dragon, one of the six original dragons, said to have created the Frost Kingdom. It was no surprise that the painter, who loved history, had painted the white dragon on the door.
TA opened the door, expecting everything to be as it always was—paint, pencils, and paper scattered everywhere, easels covering every inch of the walls. But the scene inside the room was completely different. The room was spotless, with a red velvet backdrop and a chair. Sitting on the chair was Prince Aquilo, who was painting a portrait.
"Oh, good morning, Avery! Want to see a portrait of your future king?" Aquilo asked, winking at Avery.
"Sorry, Your Highness," TA replied, beginning to search for the things Princess Carly wanted. "I'm just here to get some art supplies."
"Little one, leaving so soon?" Aquilo asked, "But I still want to see you!"
"I don't want to." Avery found the art supplies on the list and placed them in a box. "And I'm not a girl either."
The prince dismissed it. "Oh, sweetheart, you know this is just a phase! Once you grow up, it'll be fine!" he mumbled.
"I need to go." TA said, suddenly feeling uneasy because the prince was still rambling. TA recalled all the negative comments people had made about TA's gender identity. I really want to get rid of him.
"Leaving so soon?" The prince suddenly appeared at the door, ignoring the royal painter's shouts.
"This is not the behavior of a future king!" TA said sharply.
"No one will know. People won't believe you, and if that painter still values his life, he won't say anything either." The prince glanced back at the painter and then leaned in toward Avery. "What do you think of the date?" TA shivered in fear. Of course, TA had heard many threats before, but none had come from the prince, let alone from the future king.
"Do you even know what the word 'no' means?" TA snapped, shoving the prince aside.
"No," Aquilo replied with a smile. The prince, who could get whatever he wanted, of course didn't know what the word "no" meant.
Avery rolled their eyes. "Why so many people, and you specifically want to date me? How many suitors do you have? A hundred?"
He interrupted with a smile, "To be exact, over five hundred." He shook his hair, swaying in the cold wind.
"Look at me! Why me? I'm the curse of the palace." TA crossed their arms.
"You're the most beautiful girl I've ever seen." Aquilo placed a finger under Avery's chin, forcing Avery to look up at him.
